Logical vectors:

A logical vector is simply a vector of TRUE or FALSE values, but R uses them in a number of ways. In general, R will allow you to perform quantitative summaries on logical vectors, and it does this by treating:

  • TRUE is the same as 1
  • FALSE is the same as 0.

This has some fun implications! Yes, I really think this is fun why do you ask?

Run the following code and think about what it does:

numbers == 3

[1] FALSE FALSE  TRUE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE

Now lets see how R will treat this logical vector, numbers < 4, if we try to sum() it:

sum(numbers<4)

[1] 3

Exercise: What percentage of the medv measurements in the boston2 data frame are above the mean?

# Here's a guide:

# Compute the mean, save it under medv_mean
medv_mean<-mean(boston2$medv)
# find the total number of medv values above the mean
sum(boston2$medv > medv_mean)
[1] 209
# take that total number and divide by the total rows in the data frame
sum(boston2$medv > medv_mean)/nrow(boston2)
[1] 0.4130435
sum(boston2$medv > medv_mean)/length(boston2$medv)
[1] 0.4130435

The mean, 22.53, is actually the 59th percentile! (Because about 59% of the scores are smaller than the mean). Is that what we usually expect?

Percentiles, quartiles, boxplots, oh my!

The harder direction involves asking for a certain percentile of a measurement. For example, what is the 85th percentile for the crim measurement?

We rely on the quantile() command to find these quickly. To use this properly, you first put your data vector, then pass the percentile you want in next as a decimal. Lets find the 80th percentile of the crim variable:

#Place code here
# ?quantile
quantile(boston2$crim, .8)
    80% 
5.58107

We can compute a bunch of percentiles at once by passing a vector of probabilities into the probs = argument. For example, try putting c(.1, .25, .5, .75, .9) into that argument:

# Place code here.
quantile(boston2$crim, c(.1, .25, .5, .75, .9))
      10%       25%       50%       75%       90% 
 0.038195  0.082045  0.256510  3.677083 10.753000

Quartiles are a fancy way of referring to the 25th, 50th, and 75th percentiles. Specifically,

  • The first quartile \(Q_1\) is the same as the 25th percentile \(P_{25}\)
  • The first quartile \(Q_2\) is the same as the 50th percentile \(P_{50}\) (also the median)
  • The first quartile \(Q_3\) is the same as the 75th percentile \(P_{75}\)

Do you remember a command that gives the quartiles after passing in a quantitative vector?

#  take your guess!
summary(boston2$crim)

    Min.  1st Qu.   Median     Mean  3rd Qu.     Max. 
 0.00632  0.08204  0.25651  3.61352  3.67708 88.97620

Lastly, a common visualization when comparing quantitative data between groups is a boxplot.

boxplot(boston2$medv)

It is much more common to use comparative boxplots, where one produces side-by-side boxplots of a quantitative variable comparing two or more groups.

Recall that the chas variable indicates whether a Boston Suburb in the data frame is located along the Charles River (0 means No, and 1 means Yes). The code below compares the median value of homes between these two groups using comparative boxplots.

boxplot(medv ~ chas, data = boston2)

Try this out on your own. Compare the tax variable using the chas variable to create your groups.

Quick data frame slicing using dplyr

  • to get specific columns, use select()
  • to get specific rows, use filter()
    • inputs to the filter command are logical vectors

Lets create a data frame that looks at the chas and medv variables, but only includes rows where the medv is greater than the mean-value for that variable.

# data frame

# filter rows

# select columns

Boston %>%
    filter(medv > mean(medv)) %>%
    select(medv, chas)
